      "pos": [
        8596,
        8629
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "After running the experiment, you can click on the output port of the [Evaluate Model][evaluate-model] module and select <bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>Visualize<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept> to see the evaluation results (Figure 7).",
      "pos": [
        8633,
        8807
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The evaluation metrics available for binary classification models are: <bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>Accuracy<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept>, <bpt id=\"p2\">*</bpt>Precision<ept id=\"p2\">*</ept>, <bpt id=\"p3\">*</bpt>Recall<ept id=\"p3\">*</ept>, <bpt id=\"p4\">*</bpt>F1 Score<ept id=\"p4\">*</ept>, and <bpt id=\"p5\">*</bpt>AUC<ept id=\"p5\">*</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        8808,
        8936
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In addition, the module outputs a confusion matrix showing the number of true positives, false negatives, false positives, and true negatives, as well as <bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>ROC<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept>, <bpt id=\"p2\">*</bpt>Precision/Recall<ept id=\"p2\">*</ept>, and <bpt id=\"p3\">*</bpt>Lift<ept id=\"p3\">*</ept> curves.",
      "pos": [
        8937,
        9136
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Accuracy is simply the proportion of correctly classified instances.",
      "pos": [
        9138,
        9206
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "It is usually the first metric you look at when evaluating a classifier.",
      "pos": [
        9207,
        9279
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "However, when the test data is unbalanced (where most of the instances belong to one of the classes), or you are more interested in the performance on either one of the classes, accuracy doesn’t really capture the effectiveness of a classifier.",
      "pos": [
        9280,
        9524
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In the income level classification scenario, assume you are testing on some data where 99% of the instances represent people who earn less than or equal to 50K per year.",
      "pos": [
        9525,
        9694
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "It is possible to achieve a 0.99 accuracy by predicting the class “&lt;=50K” for all instances.",
      "pos": [
        9695,
        9787
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The classifier in this case appears to be doing a good job overall, but in reality, it fails to classify any of the high-income individuals (the 1%) correctly.",
      "pos": [
        9788,
        9947
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For that reason, it is helpful to compute additional metrics that capture more specific aspects of the evaluation.",
      "pos": [
        9949,
        10063
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Before going into the details of such metrics, it is important to understand the confusion matrix of a binary classification evaluation.",
      "pos": [
        10064,
        10200
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The class labels in the training set can take on only 2 possible values, which we usually refer to as positive or negative.",
      "pos": [
        10201,
        10324
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The positive and negative instances that a classifier predicts correctly are called true positives (TP) and true negatives (TN), respectively.",
      "pos": [
        10325,
        10467
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Similarly, the incorrectly classified instances are called false positives (FP) and false negatives (FN).",
      "pos": [
        10468,
        10573
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The confusion matrix is simply a table showing the number of instances that fall under each of these 4 categories.",
      "pos": [
        10574,
        10688
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Azure Machine Learning automatically decides which of the two classes in the dataset is the positive class.",
      "pos": [
        10689,
        10796
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If the class labels are Boolean or integers, then the ‘true’ or ‘1’ labeled instances are assigned the positive class.",
      "pos": [
        10797,
        10915
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If the labels are strings, as in the case of the income dataset, the labels are sorted alphabetically and the first level is chosen to be the negative class while the second level is the positive class.",
      "pos": [
        10916,
        11118
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Binary Classification Confusion Matrix",
      "pos": [
        11122,
        11160
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Figure 6.",
      "pos": [
        11221,
        11230
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Binary Classification Confusion Matrix.",
      "pos": [
        11231,
        11270
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Going back to the income classification problem, we would want to ask several evaluation questions that help us understand the performance of the classifier used.",
      "pos": [
        11272,
        11434
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "A very natural question is: ‘Out of the individuals whom the model predicted to be earning &gt;50K (TP+FP), how many were classified correctly (TP)?’",
      "pos": [
        11435,
        11581
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This question can be answered by looking at the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Precision<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> of the model, which is the proportion of positives that are classified correctly: TP/(TP+FP).",
      "pos": [
        11582,
        11737
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Another common question is “Out of all the high earning employees with income &gt;50k (TP+FN), how many did the classifier classify correctly (TP)”.",
      "pos": [
        11738,
        11883
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This is actually the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Recall<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>, or the true positive rate: TP/(TP+FN) of the classifier.",
      "pos": [
        11884,
        11973
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You might notice that there is an obvious trade-off between precision and recall.",
      "pos": [
        11974,
        12055
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For example, given a relatively balanced dataset, a classifier that predicts mostly positive instances, would have a high recall, but a rather low precision as many of the negative instances would be misclassified resulting in a large number of false positives.",
      "pos": [
        12056,
        12317
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "To see a plot of how these two metrics vary, you can click on the ‘PRECISION/RECALL’ curve in the evaluation result output page (top left part of Figure 7).",
      "pos": [
        12318,
        12474
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Binary Classification Evaluation Results",
      "pos": [
        12478,
        12518
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Figure 7.",
      "pos": [
        12577,
        12586
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Binary Classification Evaluation Results.",
      "pos": [
        12587,
        12628
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Another related metric that is often used is the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>F1 Score<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>, which takes both precision and recall into consideration.",
      "pos": [
        12630,
        12750
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "It is the harmonic mean of these 2 metrics and is computed as such: F1 = 2 (precision x recall) / (precision + recall).",
      "pos": [
        12751,
        12870
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The F1 score is a good way to summarize the evaluation in a single number, but it’s always a good practice to look at both precision and recall together to better understand how a classifier behaves.",
      "pos": [
        12871,
        13070
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In addition, one can inspect the true positive rate vs. the false positive rate in the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Receiver Operating Characteristic (ROC)<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> curve and the corresponding <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Area Under the Curve (AUC)<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> value.",
      "pos": [
        13072,
        13268
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The closer this curve is to the upper left corner, the better the classifier’s performance is (that is maximizing the true positive rate while minimizing the false positive rate).",
      "pos": [
        13269,
        13448
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Curves that are close to the diagonal of the plot, result from classifiers that tend to make predictions that are close to random guessing.",
      "pos": [
        13449,
        13588
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Using Cross Validation",
      "pos": [
        13593,
        13615
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "As in the regression example, we can perform cross validation to repeatedly train, score and evaluate different subsets of the data automatically.",
      "pos": [
        13619,
        13765
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Similarly, we can use the [Cross-Validate Model][cross-validate-model] module, an untrained logistic regression model, and a dataset.",
      "pos": [
        13766,
        13899
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The label column must be set to <bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>income<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept> in the [Cross-Validate Model][cross-validate-model] module’s properties.",
      "pos": [
        13900,
        14013
      ]
    },
    {
